The course starts with a short overview of the history of geography and introduces the development of human geography as a research field and its relations to physical geography and other social sciences. The main focus of the course is on understanding the contemporary research topics (socio-spatial processes) in human geography and discussing them. The course gives an overview of how those topics can be applied in spatial planning. The research methods used in human geography are introduced. Besides the theoretical work, study excursion and independent work are organized. Students work in groups throughout the course and present their work in written form, orally and make a video. In the end of the course students analyse their group work experience and the progress in their time management and team work skills.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course aims to introduce the history of geography, its main concepts and the contemporary topics and research methods in human geography. The course broadens the geographical viewpoint of the student and gives an overview of the studies and possible job opportunities.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  As a result of the course, the student: 1)	describes and explains the main research topis in contemporary human geography (including the research topic carried out in the Department of Geography, UT); 2)	explains and illustrates how the fundamental topics studied in human geography play a key role in spatial planning and management of the society; 3)	names and explains the development of the main theories in human geography; 4)	names and explains the basic research methodologies used in human geography; 5)	uses the main geographical terms in discussing topis about nature and society orally and in writing. 6)	has gained experience working in a group and developed his/her time management and teamwork skills.
